You can compare the cached version with the latest one fetched from the server and show a small, non‑intrusive notice if they differ:

```html
<script>
const statusEl = document.getElementById('a11yStatus');
const cacheKey = 'a11yData';
const cacheDate = 'a11yCacheDate';
const week = 7 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000;
const now = Date.now();

function render(data) {
  statusEl.textContent =
    `♿ Accessibility ${data.version} — ${data.summary} (last review ${data.date})`;
}

// Try cached data first
const cached = localStorage.getItem(cacheKey);
const cachedDate = localStorage.getItem(cacheDate);
if (cached) {
  try { render(JSON.parse(cached)); } catch {}
}

// Refresh logic
if (!cachedDate || now - cachedDate > week) {
  fetch('a11y.json')
    .then(r => r.json())
    .then(data => {
      let old = null;
      try { old = JSON.parse(cached); } catch {}
      // render fresh data and compare versions
      render(data);

      if (old && old.version && old.version !== data.version) {
        const notice = document.createElement('div');
        notice.textContent =
          `⚠️ A new accessibility audit (${data.version}) is available.`;
        notice.style.cssText =
          'font-size:0.8em;color:#b36;margin-top:0.3em;';
        statusEl.appendChild(notice);
      }

      localStorage.setItem(cacheKey, JSON.stringify(data));
      localStorage.setItem(cacheDate, now);
    })
    .catch(() => {
      statusEl.textContent = '♿ Accessibility status unavailable.';
    });
}
</script>
```

### How it behaves
- Uses cached data immediately for offline users.  
- Fetches updated `a11y.json` once a week or when the cache expires.  
- If the version string changes, a small red notice appears right below the footer text, alerting editors that the local cache was older.  

You can safely remove or hide the notice in production by adding a quick condition (e.g., show only when `window.location.hostname` matches your staging domain).

