1. Loads your page in three contexts  
   - default (light)  
   - dark‑mode preference  
   - reduced‑motion preference  

2. Captures a few DOM attributes (e.g., body class, tooltip visibility) to confirm expected behavior.

Here’s a minimal **Playwright** version (runs from Node; no build tools needed):

```js
// tests/a11y-footer.spec.js
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test.describe('Accessibility badge', () => {
  const url = 'http://localhost:8080/index.html'; // or path to your page

  test('loads badge and tooltip text', async ({ page }) => {
    await page.goto(url);
    const badge = page.locator('#a11yBadge');
    await expect(badge).toBeVisible();
    await expect(badge).toHaveAttribute(/title|aria-describedby/, /Accessibility/);
  });

  test('dark mode toggles properly', async ({ page }) => {
    await page.goto(url);
    await page.locator('#themeToggle').click();
    const body = page.locator('body');
    await expect(body).toHaveClass(/dark/);
  });

  test('respects reduced motion', async ({ page, browserName }) => {
    // simulate prefers-reduced-motion
    await page.emulateMedia({ reducedMotion: 'reduce' });
    await page.goto(url);
    const css = await page.evaluate(() => getComputedStyle(document.body).transition);
    expect(css).toBe('none');
  });
});
```

**How to run**
```bash
npm install -D @playwright/test
npx playwright test tests/a11y-footer.spec.js
```

This gives you a repeatable check that:
- the footer elements render,
- dark‑mode toggling works,
- reduce‑motion settings are honored.

